From: OpenWrt <noreply@openwrt.org>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 2026 22:00:00 -1000
Subject: [PATCH] mac80211: emit switchdev FDB DEL on STA disconnect

When a WiFi STA disconnects from an AP that is a bridge port, mac80211
does not emit a switchdev FDB DEL_TO_DEVICE event for the STA's MAC.
The bridge's FDB entry learned by the AP port stays around until the
normal bridge aging timer (default 300s) or the bridge's learn-on-rx
path eventually notices the MAC moved.

This breaks hardware flow offload on platforms that rely on switchdev
FDB events to invalidate stale PPE/WED flow entries (Airoha AN7581,
MediaTek, etc.).  After a STA roams between bands/APs or disconnects
and reconnects, the old HW flow remains bound to the stale WCID/PPE
entry and packets hit a dead path, causing connectivity to stall until
the flow times out:

  1. T=0: STA disconnects from phy0.2-ap0
  2. T=0..k: HW flow for STA MAC stays bound; PPE forwards to old WCID
  3. T=k: STA reconnects (maybe to a different band/AP)
  4. T=k+lag: bridge finally notices MAC moved, emits FDB DEL on a
     *different* port (the source port of a packet that arrives from
     the new location), triggering HW flow teardown far too late
  5. If the new flow was committed before the stale teardown,
     orphaned subflow cleanup clobbers the new flow, breaking forwarding

Fix this by emitting a SWITCHDEV_FDB_DEL_TO_DEVICE notification from
__sta_info_destroy_part2() when the STA's sdata is an AP or AP_VLAN
interface bound to a bridge port.  switchdev listeners (e.g., the
nf_flow_table FDB roaming handler, PPE drivers, DSA) immediately
tear down any HW state keyed on the STA MAC, restoring forwarding
promptly on reconnect.

The event is only emitted when:
  - CONFIG_NET_SWITCHDEV is enabled
  - sdata->vif.type is AP or AP_VLAN (matches sta_info.c's existing
    AP-oriented filters)
  - sdata->dev is currently a bridge port (so non-bridged AP setups
    incur no extra overhead)

The notification is best-effort: listeners without interest in the
event return NOTIFY_DONE and the chain proceeds.  No error path is
added; failing to notify is not fatal and matches DSA's behavior.

Signed-off-by: OpenWrt <noreply@openwrt.org>
---
--- a/net/mac80211/sta_info.c
+++ b/net/mac80211/sta_info.c
@@ -18,6 +18,10 @@
 #include <linux/timer.h>
 #include <linux/rtnetlink.h>
 
+#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_NET_SWITCHDEV)
+#include <net/switchdev.h>
+#endif
+
 #include <net/mac80211.h>
 #include "ieee80211_i.h"
 #include "driver-ops.h"
@@ -1546,6 +1550,30 @@
 	sta_dbg(sdata, "Removed STA %pM\n", sta->sta.addr);
 
 	cfg80211_del_sta_sinfo(sdata->dev, sta->sta.addr, sinfo, GFP_KERNEL);
+#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_NET_SWITCHDEV)
+	/* Notify switchdev listeners (e.g., bridge FDB roaming handlers,
+	 * PPE/WED drivers) that the STA MAC has left this AP. Without this,
+	 * hardware-offloaded flows bound to the STA's MAC persist until the
+	 * bridge ages the FDB entry out (~300s) or learns it on another
+	 * port, leaving stale HW BINDs that drop packets after reconnect.
+	 */
+	if ((sdata->vif.type == NL80211_IFTYPE_AP ||
+	     sdata->vif.type == NL80211_IFTYPE_AP_VLAN) &&
+	    netif_is_bridge_port(sdata->dev)) {
+		struct switchdev_notifier_fdb_info fdb_info = {};
+
+		fdb_info.addr = sta->sta.addr;
+		fdb_info.vid = 0;
+		fdb_info.added_by_user = false;
+		fdb_info.is_local = false;
+		fdb_info.locked = false;
+		fdb_info.offloaded = false;
+		fdb_info.info.dev = sdata->dev;
+		call_switchdev_notifiers(SWITCHDEV_FDB_DEL_TO_DEVICE,
+					 sdata->dev, &fdb_info.info, NULL);
+	}
+#endif
+
 	kfree(sinfo);
 
 	ieee80211_sta_debugfs_remove(sta);
